  "texts": [
    "Research shows that a significant portion of shares for content from \"low-credibility\" sources (those that regularly publish false or misleading info) can be attributed to bots.",
    "One study in 2024 indicated that about 33% of the top sharers of articles from dubious sites were likely automated accounts (George Washington University, 2024).",
    "This means bots can help such content leap into the mainstream conversation, whereas it might have languished in obscurity otherwise.",
    "By artificially boosting the hit counts and share counts of these articles, bots can even game platform algorithms that elevate content based on engagement metrics.",
    "This amplification is especially pernicious during elections or referendums, as false narratives from fringe outlets can get enough visibility to potentially sway undecided voters or reinforce polarized views."
  ],
